2.4 Proposition Let $(X, \mathcal{M})$ and $(Y_{\alpha}, \mathcal{N}_{\alpha})$, $\alpha \in A$, be measurable spaces. Let

$$
Y = \prod_{\alpha \in A} Y_{\alpha}, \qquad \mathcal{N} = \bigotimes_{\alpha \in A} \mathcal{N}_{\alpha},
$$

and $\pi_{\alpha}: Y \to Y_{\alpha}$ the coordinate maps. Then $f: X \to Y$ is $(\mathcal{M}, \mathcal{N})$-measurable if and only if

$$
f_{\alpha} = \pi_{\alpha} \circ f
$$

is $(\mathcal{M}, \mathcal{N}_{\alpha})$-measurable for all $\alpha \in A$.

2.5 Corollary $f: X \to \mathbb{C}$ is $\mathcal{M}$-measurable if and only if $\operatorname{Re}f$ and $\operatorname{Im}f$ are $\mathcal{M}$-measurable.

2.6 Proposition If $f, g: X \to Y$ are $\mathcal{M}$-measurable, then so are $f + g$ and $fg$.

