2.7 Proposition If $\{f_j\}$ is a sequence of $\overline{\mathbb{R}}$-valued measurable functions on $(X, \mathcal{M})$, then the functions

$$
g_1(x) = \sup_j f_j(x),
$$

$$
g_2(x) = \inf_j f_j(x),
$$

$$
g_3(x) = \lim_{j \to \infty} \sup_j f_j(x),
$$

$$
g_4(x) = \liminf_{j \to \infty} f_j(x)
$$

are all measurable. If

$$
f(x) = \lim_{j \to \infty} f_j(x) \quad \text{exists for all } x \in X,
$$

then $f$ is measurable.

