# 2.10 Theorem Let  $(X,\mathcal{M})$  be a measurable space.

If  $f: X \to [0, \infty]$  is measurable, there exists a sequence  $\{\phi_n\}$  of simple functions such that

$$
0 \leq \phi_ {1} \leq \phi_ {2} \leq \dots \leq f, \quad \phi_ {n} \rightarrow f \text { pointwise},
$$

and  $\phi_n \to f$  uniformly on any set on which  $f$  is bounded.

If  $f: X \to \mathbb{C}$  is measurable, there is a sequence  $\{\phi_n\}$  of simple functions such that

$$
0 \leq | \phi_ {1} | \leq | \phi_ {2} | \leq \dots \leq | f |, \quad \phi_ {n} \rightarrow f \text { pointwise},
$$

and  $\phi_n \to f$  uniformly on any set on which  $f$  is bounded.

