# 2.14 Monotone Convergence Theorem If $f_1, f_2, \dots \in \mathcal{L}^+$ and

$$
0 \leq f_1 \leq f_2 \leq \cdots \rightarrow f \quad \text{pointwise},
$$

then

$$
\int f \, d\mu = \lim_{n \to \infty} \int f_n \, d\mu.
$$

**Proof.** Since $0 \leq f_1 \leq f_2 \leq \cdots \leq f$,

$$
0 \leq \int f_1 \, d\mu \leq \int f_2 \, d\mu \leq \cdots \leq \int f \, d\mu.
$$

Hence

$$
\lim_{n \to \infty} \int f_n \, d\mu \leq \int f \, d\mu.
$$

Let $\phi$ be a simple function such that $0 \leq \phi \leq f$. Let $0 &lt; \alpha &lt; 1$. For $n = 1,2,\ldots$, let

$$
E_n = \{x \in X: f_n(x) \geq \alpha \phi(x)\}.
$$

Then, $E_1 \subset E_2 \subset \cdots$ and $\bigcup E_n = X$. Hence

$$
\alpha \int \phi \, d\mu = \lim_{n \to \infty} \int_{E_n} \alpha \phi \, d\mu \leq \lim_{n \to \infty} \int f_n \, d\mu.
$$

Since $0 &lt; \alpha &lt; 1$ is arbitrary, $\int \phi \, d\mu \leq \lim_{n \to \infty} \int f_n \, d\mu$. Thus,

$$
\int f \, d\mu \leq \lim_{n \to \infty} \int f_n \, d\mu.
$$

