2.15 Theorem For $f_1, f_2, \cdots \in \mathcal{L}^+$,

$$
\int \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} f_n \, d\mu = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \int f_n \, d\mu.
$$

Proof. Show: for $f, g \in \mathcal{L}^+$,

$$
\int (f + g) \, d\mu = \int f \, d\mu + \int g \, d\mu.
$$

To prove this, choose sequences $\{s_n\}$ and $\{t_n\}$ of simple functions such that

$$
0 \leq s_n \uparrow f, \quad 0 \leq t_n \uparrow g.
$$

Apply the MCT.

2.16 Proposition For $f \in \mathcal{L}^+$,

$$
\int f \, d\mu = 0 \quad \text{if and only if} \quad f = 0 \text{ a.e.}
$$

2.17 Corollary For $f_1, f_2, \ldots, f \in \mathcal{L}^+$, if $f_n \uparrow f$ a.e., then

$$
\int f \, d\mu = \lim_{n \to \infty} \int f_n \, d\mu.
$$

