Definition. A measurable function $f: X \to \mathbb{C}$ is *integrable* if

$$
\int |f| \, d\mu &lt; \infty.
$$

Definition. For an integrable function $f: X \to \mathbb{C}$, define

$$
\int f \, d\mu = \int \operatorname{Re}(f) \, d\mu + i \int \operatorname{Im}(f) \, d\mu.
$$

Remark. The space of complex-valued integrable functions is a complex vector space, and the integral is a complex-linear functional on it.

We denote this space by $L^1(\mu)$ (or $L^1(X, \mu)$, $L^1(X)$, or simply $L^1$).

Bara Kim 2026, Spring, Korea University
Real Analysis

