Definition. (i) $f_n \to f$ in measure, if for every $\varepsilon &gt; 0$,

$$
\mu \big (\{x: | f _ {n} (x) - f (x) | \geq \varepsilon \} \big) \to 0 \quad \text{as } n \to \infty.
$$

(ii) $\{f_n\}$ is Cauchy in measure, if for every $\varepsilon &gt; 0$,

$$
\mu \big (\{x: | f _ {n} (x) - f _ {m} (x) | \geq \varepsilon \} \big) \to 0 \quad \text{as } n, m \to \infty.
$$

2.29 Proposition If $f_n \to f$ in $L^1$, then $f_n \to f$ in measure.

Remark. In a finite measure space, if $f_n \to f$ a.s., then $f_n \to f$ in measure.

