2.30 Theorem (i) $\{f_n\}$ is Cauchy in measure if and only if there exists $f$ such that $f_n \to f$ in measure.

(ii) If $f_n \to f$ in measure, then there exists a subsequence $\{f_{n_j}\}$ that converges to $f$ a.e.

Proof. Suppose that $\{f_n\}$ is Cauchy in measure. Then, we can choose $\{f_{n_j}\}$ such that $\mu(E_j) &lt; 2^{-j}$, where

$$
E_j = \left\{x: \left| f_{n_j}(x) - f_{n_{j+1}}(x) \right| &gt; 2^{-j} \right\}.
$$

Note that $\mu\left(\lim \sup_{j\to \infty}E_j\right) = 0$ and $\{f_{n_j}(x)\}$ is Cauchy if $x\neq \lim \sup_{j\to \infty}E_j$.

Therefore, there exists $f$ such that $f_{n_j} \to f$ a.e. Note that for every $\varepsilon &gt; 0$ and $\eta &gt; 0$, there exists $N$ such that

$$
\mu\left(x: \left| f_n(x) - f_m(x) \right| &gt; \varepsilon / 2\right) &lt; \eta \quad \text{if } n, m \geq N.
$$

Since $f_{n_j} \to f$ a.e., we have

$$
\mu\left(x: \left| f_n(x) - f(x) \right| &gt; \varepsilon\right) &lt; \eta \quad \text{if } n \geq N.
$$

Therefore, $f_n \to f$ in measure. The rest of the proof is omitted.

