# 2.33 Egoroff's theorem Let  $f_1, f_2, \ldots$  and  $f$  be measurable complex-valued functions on  $X$  such that  $\mu(X) &lt; \infty$ .

If  $f_n \to f$  a.e., then for every  $\varepsilon &gt; 0$ , there exists  $E \subset X$  such that  $\mu(E) &lt; \varepsilon$  and  $f_n \to f$  uniformly on  $E^c$ .

Proof. Let

$$
E _ {n} (k) = \bigcup_ {m = n} ^ {\infty} \left\{x: \left| f _ {m} (x) - f (x) \right| \geq \frac {1}{k} \right\}.
$$

Then, for each  $k$

$$
E _ {1} (k) \supset E _ {2} (k) \supset \dots \quad \text {and} \quad \bigcap_ {n = 1} ^ {\infty} E _ {n} (k) = \varnothing .
$$

Given  $\varepsilon &gt; 0$  and  $k \in \mathbb{N}$ , choose  $n_k$  such that

$$
\mu \big (E _ {n _ {k}} (k) \big) &lt;   \frac {\varepsilon}{2 ^ {k}}.
$$

Let

$$
E = \bigcup_ {k = 1} ^ {\infty} E _ {n _ {k}} (k).
$$

Then  $\mu (E) &lt;   \varepsilon$  , and

$$
\left| f _ {n} (x) - f (x) \right| &lt;   \frac {1}{k} \quad \text {if} n &gt; n _ {k} \text {and} x \notin E.
$$

