Let $(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)$ and $(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)$ be measure spaces.

We will construct the product measure $\mu \times \nu$ on $\mathcal{M} \otimes \mathcal{N}$.

A (measurable) rectangle in $X \times Y$ is a set of the form

$$
A \times B \quad \text{with} \quad A \in \mathcal{M} \text{ and } B \in \mathcal{N}.
$$

Let $\mathcal{A}$ be the algebra generated by measurable rectangles. Note that $\mathcal{A}$ is the collection of sets which are finite disjoint unions of measurable rectangles.

For any $E = \bigcup_{j=1}^{n} A_j \times B_j \in \mathcal{A}$, where $A_j \times B_j$, $j = 1, \ldots, n$, are disjoint, define

$$
\pi(E) = \sum_{j=1}^{n} \mu(A_j) \, \nu(B_j).
$$

Remark. $\pi$ is well defined on $\mathcal{A}$.

Bara Kim 2026, Spring, Korea University

Real Analysis

---

2.1 Measurable functions 000000000
2.2 Nonnegative functions 00000000
2.3 Complex functions 000000000
2.4 Mode of Convergence 0000
2.5 Product measures 00000000000

Note that for any $E = \bigcup_{j=1}^{n} A_{j} \times B_{j} \in \mathcal{A}$, where $A_{j} \times B_{j}$ are disjoint,

$$
\begin{array}{l}
\pi (E) = \sum_{j = 1}^{n} \mu (A_{j}) \nu (B_{j}) \\
= \int_{Y} \int_{X} \sum_{j = 1}^{n} \chi_{A_{j}} (x) \chi_{B_{j}} (y) d \mu (x) d \nu (y) \\
= \int_{Y} \int_{X} \chi_{E} (x, y) d \mu (x) d \nu (y).
\end{array}
$$

If $E_1 \subset E_2 \subset \cdots$, $\bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty} E_k = E$ and $E_1, E_2, \ldots, E \in \mathcal{A}$, then

$$
\begin{array}{l}
\lim_{k \rightarrow \infty} \pi (E_{k}) = \lim_{k \rightarrow \infty} \int_{Y} \left[ \int_{X} \chi_{E_{k}} (x, y) d \mu (x) \right] d \nu (y) \\
= \int_{Y} \left[ \lim_{k \rightarrow \infty} \int_{X} \chi_{E_{k}} (x, y) d \mu (x) \right] d \nu (y) \\
= \int_{Y} \int_{X} \lim_{k \rightarrow \infty} \chi_{E_{k}} (x, y) d \mu (x) d \nu (y) \\
= \int_{Y} \int_{X} \chi_{E} (x, y) d \mu (x) d \nu (y) \\
= \pi (E).
\end{array}
$$

Therefore, $\pi$ is a premeasure on $\mathcal{A}$.

Bara Kim 2026, Spring, Korea University
