2.36 Theorem Let $(X, \mathcal{M}, \mu)$ and $(Y, \mathcal{N}, \nu)$ be $\sigma$-finite measure spaces. If $E \in \mathcal{M} \otimes \mathcal{N}$, then

$$
x \mapsto \nu(E_x) \quad \text{is measurable on } X, \tag{a}
$$

$$
y \mapsto \mu(E^y) \quad \text{is measurable on } Y, \tag{b}
$$

and

$$
(\mu \times \nu)(E) = \int \nu(E_x) \, d\mu(x) = \int \mu(E^y) \, d\nu(y). \tag{c}
$$

Proof. First, suppose that $\mu$ and $\nu$ are finite. Let

$$
\mathcal{C} = \{E \in \mathcal{M} \otimes \mathcal{N} : \text{(a), (b) and (c) hold} \}.
$$

Then, $\mathcal{C}$ contains the algebra generated by measurable rectangles.

Also, $\mathcal{C}$ is a monotone class. (Here, we use the finiteness of $\mu$ and $\nu$.)

Hence, $\mathcal{C}$ contains the $\sigma$-algebra generated by measurable rectangles, $\mathcal{M} \otimes \mathcal{N}$. Therefore, $\mathcal{C} = \mathcal{M} \otimes \mathcal{N}$, and so (a), (b) and (c) hold for all $E \in \mathcal{M} \otimes \mathcal{N}$.

Remark. Without the $\sigma$-finiteness assumption, the result can fail, although explicit counterexamples are technically difficult to construct.

