Next, if $\mu$ and $\nu$ are $\sigma$-finite, choose $X_j$ and $Y_j$ such that

$$
\mu(X_j) &lt; \infty, \quad X_1 \subset X_2 \subset \cdots, \quad \bigcup X_j = X,
$$

$$
\nu(Y_j) &lt; \infty, \quad Y_1 \subset Y_2 \subset \cdots, \quad \bigcup Y_j = Y.
$$

Note

$$
x \mapsto \nu(E_x \cap (X_j \times Y_j)) \quad \text{is measurable on } X,
$$

$$
y \mapsto \mu(E^y \cap (X_j \times Y_j)) \quad \text{is measurable on } Y,
$$

and

$$
\begin{aligned}
(\mu \times \nu)(E \cap (X_j \times Y_j)) &amp;= \int \nu\left((E \cap (X_j \times Y_j))_x\right) d\mu(x) \\
&amp;= \int \mu\left((E \cap (X_j \times Y_j))^y\right) d\nu(y).
\end{aligned}
$$

Letting $j \to \infty$ proves the desired results.

