# 2.37 Fubini-Tonelli Theorem Let  $(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)$  and  $(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)$  be  $\sigma$ -finite measure spaces.

1 (Tonelli) If  $f \in L^{+}(X \times Y)$ , then

$$
g (x) = \int f _ {x} d v \in L ^ {+} (X), \qquad h (y) = \int f ^ {y} d \mu \in L ^ {+} (Y),
$$

and

$$
\int f d (\mu \times \nu) = \int \left[ \int f (x, y) d \nu (y) \right] d \mu (x) = \int \left[ \int f (x, y) d \mu (x) \right] d \nu (y). \quad (*)
$$

2 (Fubini) If  $f \in L^{1}(\mu \times \nu)$  (possibly complex valued), then

(i) we have

$$
f _ {x} \in L ^ {1} (v) \text { for a.e. } x \in X,
$$

$$
f ^ {y} \in L ^ {1} (\mu) \text { for a.e. } y \in Y,
$$

(ii) we have

$$
g (x) = \int f _ {x} d v \in L ^ {1} (\mu) \quad (g (x) \text { is defined for } \mu \text {- a . e . } x),
$$

$$
h (y) = \int f ^ {y} d \mu \in L ^ {1} (v) \quad (h (y) \text { is defined for } v \text {- a . e . } y),
$$

and

(iii)  $(\ast)$  holds.

