Remark. Let $(X, \mathcal{M}, \mu)$ and $(Y, \mathcal{N}, \mu)$ be $\sigma$-finite measure spaces.

Let $(X, \overline{\mathcal{M}}, \overline{\mu})$ be the completion of $(X, \mathcal{M}, \mu)$, and let $(Y, \overline{\mathcal{N}}, \overline{\nu})$ be the completion of $(Y, \mathcal{N}, \nu)$. Then,

$$
\left(X \times Y, \overline {{\mathcal {M} \otimes \mathcal {N}}}, \overline {{\mu \times \bar {\nu}}}\right) = \left(X \times Y, \overline {{\mathcal {M} \otimes \mathcal {N}}}, \overline {{\mu \times \nu}}\right),
$$

where $(X\times Y,\overline{\mathcal{M}\otimes\mathcal{N}},\overline{\mu\times\bar{\nu}})$ is the completion of $(X\times Y,\overline{\mathcal{M}}\otimes \overline{\mathcal{N}},\overline{\mu}\times \overline{\nu})$, and $(X\times Y,\overline{\mathcal{M}\otimes\mathcal{N}},\overline{\mu\times\nu})$ is the completion of $(X\times Y,\mathcal{M}\otimes \mathcal{N},\mu \times \nu)$.

